Goal¶

Using the data collected from existing customers, build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.¶

Attribute information¶

Input variables: Bank client data:

  1. age: Continuous feature
  2. job: Type of job (management, technician, entrepreneur, blue-collar, etc.)
  3. marital: marital status (married, single, divorced)
  4. education: education level (primary, secondary, tertiary)
  5. default: has credit in default?
  6. housing: has housing loan?
  7. loan: has personal loan?
  8. balance in account Related to previous contact:
  9. contact: contact communication type
  10. month: last contact month of year
  11. day: last contact day of the month
  12. duration: last contact duration, in seconds* Other attributes:
  13. campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client
  14. pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (-1 tells us the person has not been contacted or contact period is beyond 900 days)
  15. previous: number of times the client has been contacted before for the last campaign to subscribe term deposit
  16. poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign Output variable (desired target):
  17. Target: Tell us has the client subscribed a term deposit. (Yes, No)

Outlier Treatment¶

We can use Capping and Flooring¶

Decide the upper and lower limit and values above that will be considered as outlier

Exponential Smoothening¶

Extrapolate a curve between 95 and 99 percentile and bring the values to fall on the curves going out of the range P95 and P99

Sigma Approach¶

Identify outliers by capturing all the values falling outside mean +- (sigma)(value)

In [17]:
# Using capping and flooring to treat the outliers for age
np.percentile(data.age,[99])
np.percentile(data.age,[99])[0]
age_uv = np.percentile(data.age,[99])[0]
data[(data.age > age_uv)]
data.age[(data.age > 3*age_uv)] = 3*age_uv

Insight

  • No two features are highly correlated.
  • People with No credit are subscribing.
  • People having no personal loan are subscribing.
  • Target does not really depend on the features except duration, pdays, housing loan and poutcome variables. Target is fairly positively correlated with duration i.e. the longer the duration of the last call was, the greater is the chance of the target accepting the term deposit. Target is slightly positively correlated with poutcome feature. It means that if the poutcome is known and if it the previous marketing campaign was a success, the target is more likely to take the term deposit. Target is slightly negatively correlated with pdays which means that the if the number of days passed since the previous campaign increases without contacting the target, it is less likely for them to accept the term deposit.

# Importing useful libraries
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve,auc
from sklearn.metrics import recall_score,classification_report, precision_score, f1_score, accuracy_score, confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve

## defining a function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_confusion_matrix( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
    
# defining a function to print out model results
def print_results(regression_model, x_test, y_test, y_predict):
    print("Training accuracy:",regression_model.score(x_train,y_train))  
    print()
    print("Testing Accuracy:",regression_model.score(x_test, y_test))
    print()
    print("Recall:",recall_score(y_test,y_predict))
    print()
    print("Precision:",precision_score(y_test,y_predict))
    print()
    print("F1 Score:",f1_score(y_test,y_predict))
    print()
    print("Roc Auc Score:",roc_auc_score(y_test,y_predict))
    print()
    print('Confusion Matrix')
    print(draw_confusion_matrix(y_test,y_predict))

# defining a function to draw area under the curve
def draw_curve(regression_model,y_test,x_test):
    logit_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, regression_model.predict(x_test))
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, regression_model.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1])
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='Logistic Regression (area = %0.2f)' % logit_roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.savefig('Log_ROC')
    plt.show()

Conclusion¶

We are getting the highest accuracy using Random Forest , Bagging Classifier, Ada Boosting, Gradient Boosting and XGBoost.¶
Taking into consideration everything together i.e. Recall, Precision, F1 Score as well as ROC AUC score XGBoost gives the best result.¶
Hence, I would recomment XGBoost in this case as it takes care of everything and not only the accuracy.¶
It means that the model will predict 90% correctly the customers who will subscribe term deposit and who will not.¶
